  "reasoning": "The chain of evidence begins with the ancient world's association of divinity with eye conditions, first documented in Egypt. This general concept evolved into specific narratives of divine intervention in sight in both Greek (Homer's Iliad) and Hebrew (Genesis) traditions. Within the Jewish context, this idea was further refined into a specific Messianic prophecy (Isaiah, Dead Sea Scrolls), which directly set the theological stage for the New Testament accounts of Jesus healing the blind. The Gospels codified these accounts in the 1st century CE, with early manuscript evidence confirming their existence by the 2nd century. Later artistic retellings show the story's continued cultural importance. There is high confidence in this general trajectory, though the exact dating of oral traditions and ancient texts always carries some uncertainty.",
